                <h2>How Long Do PRP Side Effects Last?</h2>

                <p>One of the most reassuring aspects of PRP side effects is how quickly they resolve. Here is a detailed timeline:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>First 1 to 6 hours:</strong> Mild redness, minor bleeding at injection points (stops quickly), mild swelling begins. Some patients feel a dull ache or throbbing.</li>
                    <li><strong>6 to 24 hours:</strong> Swelling peaks. Redness remains visible, especially on the face. Tenderness is at its highest. Headache (if any) typically occurs in this window.</li>
                    <li><strong>24 to 48 hours:</strong> Swelling begins to subside. Redness fades significantly. Most discomfort resolves. Bruising (if present) becomes visible as small purple or yellowish marks.</li>
                    <li><strong>48 to 72 hours:</strong> The majority of side effects have resolved by this point. Some residual tenderness may remain.</li>
                    <li><strong>3 to 7 days:</strong> Any remaining bruising fades. Itching may occur briefly as the area heals. The treatment area feels completely normal for most patients.</li>
                    <li><strong>1 to 4 weeks:</strong> Temporary hair shedding (if it occurs) happens during this window and resolves on its own as new growth begins.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>In summary, the vast majority of PRP side effects are completely resolved within 3 to 5 days. The temporary shedding phase is the only effect that extends beyond the first week, and even that is a sign the treatment is working.</p>

                <h2>How to Minimise PRP Side Effects</h2>

                <p>While most side effects are mild and unavoidable, there are practical steps you can take before and after your PRP session to reduce their severity and duration.</p>

                <h3>Before Your PRP Session</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Stop blood-thinning supplements:</strong> Discontinue fish oil, vitamin E, ginkgo biloba, and garlic supplements 5 to 7 days before the procedure. These increase bruising risk.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid aspirin and ibuprofen:</strong> Do not take NSAIDs (non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs) for at least 5 days before PRP. These medications interfere with platelet function and can reduce treatment effectiveness.</li>
                    <li><strong>Stay hydrated:</strong> Drink plenty of water in the 24 hours before your appointment. Good hydration makes the blood draw easier and reduces the risk of dizziness and headache.</li>
                    <li><strong>Eat a nutritious meal:</strong> Do not arrive on an empty stomach. A light, balanced meal 1 to 2 hours before the procedure helps prevent light-headedness.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid alcohol:</strong> Do not consume alcohol for at least 48 hours before PRP. Alcohol thins the blood and increases bruising and swelling.</li>
                    <li><strong>Wash your hair or face:</strong> Arrive with a clean treatment area. For scalp PRP, wash your hair the morning of the appointment. For facial PRP, come with clean, makeup-free skin.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>After Your PRP Session</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Do not wash the treated area for 24 hours:</strong> Allow the PRP to fully absorb into the tissue before washing.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid strenuous exercise for 48 hours:</strong> Heavy workouts increase blood flow and can worsen swelling and bruising.</li>
                    <li><strong>Skip saunas, steam rooms, and hot baths:</strong> Excessive heat can increase inflammation. Avoid for 48 to 72 hours.</li>
                    <li><strong>Do not apply ice directly:</strong> While it may be tempting to ice the swollen area, cold compresses can reduce the inflammatory response that PRP relies on to work. Only use ice if specifically advised by your doctor.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid hair styling products for 24 hours:</strong> Gels, sprays, and serums may irritate the injection sites on the scalp.</li>
                    <li><strong>Use paracetamol for pain if needed:</strong> Avoid aspirin and ibuprofen as they can inhibit the platelet healing process.</li>
                    <li><strong>Sleep slightly elevated:</strong> If you experience facial swelling, sleeping with an extra pillow can help reduce it overnight.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid sun exposure:</strong> Protect the treated area from direct sunlight for 48 to 72 hours. Use a hat for scalp PRP and broad-spectrum sunscreen for facial PRP.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>PRP Side Effects vs Other Hair Loss Treatments</h2>

                <p>To put PRP side effects in perspective, let us compare them with the side effects of other common hair loss treatments.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Minoxidil</h3>
                <p>Minoxidil (commonly sold as Rogaine or Mintop) is a topical medication applied daily to the scalp. While effective, its side effects include persistent scalp irritation, dryness, flaking, unwanted facial hair growth (especially in women), and in rare cases, dizziness or rapid heartbeat. These side effects continue for as long as you use the product — which is indefinitely. PRP side effects, by contrast, are limited to a few days after each session and do not involve any ongoing daily commitment.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Finasteride</h3>
                <p>Finasteride (Propecia, Finpecia) is an oral prescription medication that blocks DHT. It is effective for male pattern baldness but carries a well-documented risk of sexual side effects including reduced libido, erectile dysfunction, and decreased ejaculate volume. Some patients report persistent side effects even after stopping the medication — a condition termed "post-finasteride syndrome." PRP has absolutely no hormonal or sexual side effects, making it a preferred option for patients who are concerned about these risks.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Hair Transplant Surgery</h3>
                <p><a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">Hair transplant surgery</a> is a highly effective but invasive procedure. Side effects and risks include surgical pain, significant swelling (lasting 3 to 5 days), numbness in the donor and recipient areas (lasting weeks to months), visible scabbing and crusting, risk of infection, scarring, shock loss, and a recovery period of 2 to 4 weeks before returning to normal activities. PRP is non-surgical, involves no incisions, and has essentially zero downtime. Many patients use PRP both before and after a hair transplant to enhance results and speed recovery.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Mesotherapy</h3>
                <p>Mesotherapy involves injecting a cocktail of vitamins, minerals, and medications into the scalp. Because it introduces foreign substances (unlike PRP which uses your own blood), the risk of allergic reactions is higher. Side effects include more pronounced swelling, bruising, and in rare cases, skin necrosis or granuloma formation. PRP carries none of these risks because it is autologous — derived entirely from your own body.</p>

                <h2>When to Contact Your Doctor After PRP</h2>

                <p>While PRP side effects are overwhelmingly mild and self-limiting, there are certain warning signs that warrant immediate medical attention. <a href="../contact.php">Contact your doctor or clinic</a> if you experience any of the following after PRP treatment:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Increasing pain after 48 hours:</strong> Post-PRP discomfort should be decreasing, not increasing. Worsening pain beyond 48 hours could indicate an issue.</li>
                    <li><strong>Signs of infection:</strong> Increasing redness with warmth, pus or discharge from injection sites, red streaking around the treated area, or fever above 100.4 F (38 C).</li>
                    <li><strong>Severe or spreading swelling:</strong> Mild swelling is normal, but if it spreads significantly beyond the treated area or does not begin to improve within 48 to 72 hours, seek evaluation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Persistent numbness or tingling:</strong> Brief tingling is not unusual, but numbness that persists for more than a few days should be assessed.</li>
                    <li><strong>Excessive or prolonged bleeding:</strong> The injection sites should stop bleeding within minutes. Ongoing bleeding suggests a clotting concern that needs attention.</li>
                    <li><strong>Allergic reaction symptoms:</strong> While exceedingly rare with PRP, any signs of hives, difficulty breathing, or facial swelling unrelated to the treatment area require immediate medical attention.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>It is worth emphasising that these complications are extremely rare. In thousands of PRP sessions performed at DenceSpot Clinic, serious adverse events are virtually unheard of. However, being vigilant and knowing when to seek help is always wise.</p>

